# Part I — The Vision

## 1. The problem

By mid-2026, autonomous AI agents have stopped being a curiosity and become infrastructure. Tools like OpenClaw demonstrated that an agent connected to your apps and given the ability to *act* — not just talk — changes how work gets done. OpenClaw surpassed 100,000 GitHub stars within weeks of taking its name, and the agentic-workflow pattern now generates more than half of all output tokens on some major model-routing platforms.

But this first generation revealed three deep problems.

**They burn tokens recklessly.** Multi-agent systems routinely consume four to fifteen times more tokens than a single well-formed call when they are not carefully optimised. Every redundant thought, every re-sent context window, every chatty handoff between agents costs money and, less visibly, energy. The current approach treats the language model as a hammer for every nail. This is wasteful in a way that compounds: at planetary scale, careless agent design is an environmental cost, not just a financial one.

**They are monolithic.** The dominant frameworks bundle everything together. When teams outgrow the framework's assumptions, they hit a wall. One production team, after a year of fighting their framework's abstractions, removed it entirely and reported that "once we removed it, we could just code." A framework should be a trellis that supports growth, not a cage that constrains it.

**They are unsafe by accident.** Agents granted broad system access, exposed to untrusted content, and able to communicate externally form what Simon Willison named the "lethal trifecta" — the precise conditions for prompt-injection and data-exfiltration attacks. Security in most agent platforms is an afterthought bolted on, not a foundation built in.

Wyrtloom is a response to all three.

## 2. The philosophy

Wyrtloom is built on a single guiding belief: **the language model is the most expensive consultant in the building, so you only call it when no cheaper mechanism will do.**

Everything follows from this. Before a token is ever spent, the system does as much deterministic, coded work as possible. A small, cheap model parses intent. A tool engine does the heavy lifting. The expensive frontier model is engaged only at the genuine decision points — and when it is, the prompt is designed to extract as much useful output from a single turn as the model's output budget allows.

This is not only thrift. It is a green principle. Saving tokens saves energy. A system that gets *more efficient over time* — that learns to need its expensive consultant less and less — is a system that treads more lightly on the world. That is the heart of Wyrtloom.

Three further principles shape everything:

**Minimal core, everything else a plugin.** The core is the smallest possible kernel that can bootstrap the system and guarantee a stable, portable ecosystem. It must be small enough that two or three people could maintain it indefinitely. Every capability — providers, memory, UIs, the machine-learning tuner, even the sandbox runtime — is a plugin behind a stable interface.

**Interfaces are sacred; implementations are free.** The lesson of every fragmented ecosystem is that breaking an interface cascades failures across everything built on it. Wyrtloom commits to stable, versioned interface contracts from day one. The shape of a message, a capability declaration, a task handoff — these are public promises. What sits behind them can be swapped freely.

**Security is a first-class citizen, present before anything else breathes.** Security is not a plugin you add. It is the root of trust that initialises first, verifies the loader, and stamps every message that crosses the system. It learns malicious patterns over time and shares what it learns, like a forest's mycelial network alerting its neighbours to a pathogen.

## 3. The metaphor

A forest floor is not chaos. Beneath it runs the mycelium — a vast fungal network that connects the trees, channels nutrients to where they are needed, and acts as an immune membrane, detecting and destroying pathogens. When one tree is attacked, the network warns the others, and they arm their defences before the threat arrives.

Wyrtloom is built in this image. Agents are woven together from a minimal rooted core. Work and nutrients (context, tokens) flow only where needed. The security layer is the immune membrane. Threat intelligence propagates between installations faster than attacks can spread. And the whole system is designed to grow richer and more efficient the longer it lives — composting its own experience into reusable code, the way a forest builds soil.

## 4. How Wyrtloom works (a tour)

A **human** gives Wyrtloom a task — through a chat interface, a CLI, or eventually a messaging channel like Discord. Each human has a profile, so their interactions are clearly attributed.

The task lands on a **Kanban board**, the single source of truth for what needs doing, who is doing it, and what is stuck. This idea is borrowed directly from Hermes Agent, whose durable Kanban board turns multi-agent collaboration into a first-class primitive. Tasks move through clear states — backlog, todo, ready, running, blocked, done, archived — and the board, not chatter between agents, is how everyone knows the state of the world. This dramatically reduces the wasteful back-and-forth that plagues multi-agent systems.

Before any expensive work begins, a **pre-digestion pipeline** runs: parse the intent cheaply, plan deterministically, do as much with coded tools as possible, and only *then* hand a tightly-scoped problem to a language model. Each task carries a **task profile** that shapes its environment — which tools it can see, how much context it receives, and how readily it should ask for help rather than flailing. A narrow, well-scoped agent is both cheaper and more reliable than one given everything and told to figure it out.

When a model *is* called, every detail is **logged** — provider, model, tokens in, tokens out, cost, outcome. This log is the raw material for the future machine-learning tuner that will, over time, learn which model is worth its price for which kind of task, and how to shape prompts for maximum single-turn yield.

Agents work in isolation where their work might collide — each on its own Git branch, with artifact-level locking so two agents never fight over the same file. An **orchestrator** watches for stalls and tries gently to revive a stuck agent before escalating to a human. When a human *is* needed, the board shows it clearly, with suggested actions as buttons, a free-text box, and a stop button.

Everything an agent can do is mediated by the **security layer**. Plugins come in two classes: *safe* plugins run fully sandboxed in WebAssembly and can be shared and installed automatically; *unsafe* plugins, which need real system access, declare their required capabilities upfront like an app requesting permissions, and a human must approve them. Every message crossing the system earns a security "stamp"; if it is transformed, the stamp is void and must be re-earned. Dangerous actions — a shell command, a file deletion — are rated for their potential side effects, and routed accordingly: passed, logged, escalated, or blocked.

Over time, Wyrtloom is designed to **improve itself**. It reviews its own logs for patterns that recur often enough to be worth turning into deterministic code — "crystallising" expensive LLM habits into cheap functions. Trusted installations share threat intelligence and safe plugins, forming a commons that grows more capable and more secure together.

## 5. What Wyrtloom is not

It is not a monolith. It is not a framework that dictates how you must think. It is not a system that treats the language model as the answer to everything. It is not secure-by-afterthought. And it is not finished — it is a seed, designed to grow along a deliberate path.

