## Appendix B — Plugin model and security architecture (full)

This appendix records the complete intended security and plugin architecture. Only the parts marked **(v0.1)** are built in the first milestone; the rest is reserved design that the v0.1 interfaces must not preclude.

### B.1 Plugin classes

- **SAFE plugins (v0.1 interface).** No system access. Run fully sandboxed in WebAssembly. Because they structurally cannot form the "lethal trifecta" (private data + untrusted content + external comms), they may be shared and installed automatically between trusted installations. A SAFE plugin that declares *any* system capability is rejected at load.
- **UNSAFE plugins (v0.1 interface; human approval Phase 3).** Need real system access (file I/O, network, shell, git). Must declare required capabilities in their manifest, in the manner of mobile-app permissions. A human must approve capability grants; the community trust score modulates how much friction that approval carries.

### B.2 The plugin marketplace and trust (Phase 3 — parked)

- Agents may auto-publish SAFE plugins to a shared platform and auto-consume them.
- **Three-layer trust:** a score attached to the *plugin*, the *agent* that produced it, and the *owner* behind that agent.
- A low-trust plugin is subjected to a mandatory LLM **security scan** before integration; a high-trust plugin is streamlined but still sandboxed.
- **Anti-abuse**, designed against the npm supply-chain lesson that trust without verification is exploited within days: cryptographic signing binds author identity to plugin; trust is time-weighted and cannot be farmed quickly (Sybil resistance); sudden trust spikes are flagged; the community can flag suspicious plugins; flagged plugins are quarantined pending review; inactive or flagged accounts suffer trust decay; and owner verification (KYC-lite) is required before an agent may publish.

### B.3 The security gate and the passport stamp (full model; minimal in v0.1)

A single security gate is applied to a message **once per form it takes**.

- On entry, the message is checked (identity, signature/origin, and — in the full model — content danger) and, if it passes, **stamped**. The stamp asserts "this *form* of this message passed the gate."
- If the message is later **transformed or translated**, the stamp is **invalidated**, exactly like a passport stamp voided when you cross a new border. The new form must earn a fresh stamp.
- v0.1 has no translation layer, so the gate runs once in practice — but the **invalidation-on-transform rule is implemented and tested now**, so the contract is honoured when translation arrives.

### B.4 Contract security specs and danger rating (Phase 3 — parked)

Every contract definition will carry a **security spec**: field-level danger ratings (low / medium / high / critical), risk-typed fields (e.g. `shell_command`, `file_path`, `url`, `code`), and human-readable side-effect descriptions. Dangerous typed fields are rated by a small, cheap LLM before execution, and routed by policy:

```
low      → pass silently
medium   → log
high     → escalate to human
critical → block + alert
```

### B.5 Behavioural anomaly detection and the immune system (Phase 3 — parked)

The security module will track each plugin's behaviour against a baseline of its declared role. A plugin acting dangerously outside its role triggers a graduated response — **log → rate-limit → block → quarantine + report**. Confirmed malicious patterns are shareable, cryptographically signed, between trusted installations, which may subscribe to threat feeds. This is the mycelial immune membrane: installations learn from one another's encounters, so defences spread faster than attacks.

### B.6 The security policy engine (Phase 3 — parked)

The security module exposes its own plugin interface for **policy handlers**, so new security contexts can be handled without changing the core. Example: an agent present on a Discord channel grants different tool permissions to verified versus unverified users. Policy plugins are themselves SAFE-class and sandboxed, and cannot self-escalate. All policy decisions are logged by the core module.

## Appendix C — Concurrency, Git, and the orchestrator (Phase 2 — parked)

- **Locking.** One agent should not begin work that depends on artifacts another agent is changing. Locking is **artifact-level**, not merely project-level, so concurrency is permitted wherever separation of concerns allows. Observer (read-only) access for supervision is possible but must guard against the read-then-write race.
- **Git by default.** Each agent works on its own clone/branch, giving conflict detection for free (via merge conflicts), full audit trail, and rollback.
- **The orchestrator.** An orchestrating agent detects stalls and responds in graduated fashion: first a soft "prod" with a hint injected, up to a configurable hard limit of restarts (default 3), then escalation to a human. As much of this logic as possible is **coded, not LLM-driven**, to save tokens.
- **Avoiding handoff loops.** Agents coordinate through the Kanban board (shared state) rather than chatting, which removes most messaging. Where they do message, communication is via typed contracts; a configurable hop limit (default 3) and cycle detection (the same task id appearing twice in a chain) prevent the wasteful back-and-forth that inflates multi-agent token costs.

## Appendix D — ML tuner, memory, and self-improvement (Phase 4 — parked)

- **The ML tuner** is a **lightweight classical model** by default (a bandit algorithm, gradient-boosted trees, or simple reinforcement learning), training **locally** on the call logs. It assists agent/model selection and prompt design for efficiency. It deliberately **sacrifices explainability** for low compute cost — decisions are logged for audit but not narrated. The tuner is itself exposed as a **swappable plugin interface**, so neural or cloud-offload trainers can replace it later. Its training signal is cost-efficiency: *was the more expensive model worth it for this task type?*
- **Tool prediction** progresses through three stages over the system's life: coded rules first (free, deterministic), then LLM assistance for ambiguous cases, then a learned keyword/phrase model. Human override is always available.
- **Code crystallisation.** A periodic inspector reviews session logs for LLM-call patterns that recur often enough to be re-implemented as deterministic code, and flags them for human-approved promotion to a plugin. This is how Wyrtloom composts experience into soil — needing its expensive consultant less over time.
- **Distillation** of logs into a local model for cheaper inference is attractive but compute-constrained; it is scheduled for low-activity windows and deferred until resources allow.
- **Memory** is a **pluggable provider** (e.g. Mem0, a vector DB, or simple SQLite full-text search), keeping the core minimal. Lifetime-context search runs at query time through this provider. Modern token-efficient memory algorithms retrieve in roughly 7,000 tokens what naive full-context approaches spend 26,000 on — a large, recurring saving.

## Appendix E — The Car Park (phased roadmap)

The complete requirements register, partitioned by milestone. v0.1 builds only the first block; everything else is parked here, designed-for but not built, so the seed stays small while the path stays clear.

### v0.1 — "The Seed" (36 requirements)
Minimal core; Rust; TDD; Kanban state-machine contract + SQLite; one LLM provider; one hard-coded profile; WASM sandbox (wasmtime); message-bus primitive + Tokio default; plugin loader + manifest; minimal security gate; call logger; CLI escalation; agent message types defined; bootstrap order; semantic versioning + backward-compat policy; token-efficiency plumbing; name Wyrtloom; Apache 2.0.

### Phase 2 — Multi-user & collaboration
Human profiles with per-user attribution; project- and artifact-level locking; concurrency via separation of concerns; Git-by-default with per-agent branches; full Kanban UI with the buttons + free-text + stop pattern; multiple boards per profile domain; the orchestrator with graduated restart; cheap-LLM intent parsing; agent hop limits, cycle detection, and board-as-shared-state messaging; a second (Anthropic) provider; per-model cost config; auto-pulled pricing; efficiency tracking; retry/fallback plugin.

### Phase 3 — Marketplace, trust & deep security
Plugin marketplace; three-layer trust; LLM security scan for low-trust plugins; cryptographic signing; anti-abuse (rate limiting, time-weighted trust, anomaly detection, flagging, quarantine, trust decay, KYC-lite); the security policy engine with policy-handler plugins; the passport-stamp two-phase validation; contract security specs with danger ratings; LLM danger rating; behavioural anomaly detection; shared threat intelligence and feed subscription.

### Phase 4 — Self-improvement
The ML tuner (lightweight, local, swappable, non-explainable); cost-efficiency training signal; three-stage tool prediction; code crystallisation; scheduled distillation; pluggable memory provider; lifetime-context search.

### Phase 5 — Profiles & onboarding
Full task-profile model (tool set + context shape + escalation threshold); human override everywhere; LLM-guided profile-setup chat on first config; the contract manager (registry + version negotiation); translation plugin interface; cross-instance agent handoffs.

### Deferred indefinitely
Local-model distillation while compute-constrained; a formal RFC/governance process (noted as needed before v1.0 or first external contributors).

## Appendix F — Reference platforms and grounding research

Wyrtloom's design is anchored in observed reality, not speculation. Key references and the lessons drawn from each:

**OpenClaw** (TypeScript/Swift; MIT; Gateway + Agent + Skills + Memory). Demonstrated demand for self-hosted agents that *act*. Its noted weakness — session memory requiring manual setup — informs Wyrtloom's pluggable memory provider. *Source: https://www.kdnuggets.com/openclaw-explained-the-free-ai-agent-tool-going-viral-already-in-2026 ; https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenClaw*

**Hermes Agent** (Nous Research). Source of the Kanban model — a SQLite-backed, durable board with states, dependencies, and a dispatcher that turns multi-agent work into a first-class primitive; skills use progressive disclosure to minimise tokens. *Source: https://hermes-agent.nousresearch.com/docs/user-guide/features/kanban ; https://magnus919.com/2026/05/the-hermes-kanban-a-complete-guide-to-multi-agent-task-orchestration/*

**Simon Willison — sandboxing.** The `micropython-wasm` / MicroQuickJS approach (a customised WASM build run via wasmtime) is the model for SAFE-plugin sandboxing; his "lethal trifecta" framing (private data + untrusted content + external comms) shapes the SAFE/UNSAFE split. *Source: https://simonwillison.net/tags/sandboxing/ ; https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Willison*

**Token-efficiency research.** Multi-agent systems consume 4–15× the tokens of single calls if unoptimised; sparsification (S²-MAD) and action-chaining (ELHPlan) achieve large reductions; the DEPO paper (AAAI 2026) frames dual efficiency across both per-step tokens and trajectory-level calls. These ground Wyrtloom's central thesis. *Source: https://www.obviousworks.ch/en/token-optimization-saves-up-to-80-percent-llm-costs/ ; https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.08545 ; https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.15392*

**Plugin-architecture failure lessons.** LangChain's over-abstraction (a team's eventual "once we removed it, we could just code"); the cascade danger of breaking interface changes; the npm supply-chain blast radius; and maintainer-burnout collapse (Ingress-Nginx) collectively justify the thin-interface, sacred-versioning, crypto-signing, and small-maintainable-core principles. *Source: https://shashankguda.medium.com/challenges-criticisms-of-langchain-b26afcef94e7 ; https://medium.com/@nraman.n6/versioning-rollback-lifecycle-management-of-ai-agents-treating-intelligence-as-deployable-deac757e4dea ; https://thenewstack.io/open-source-inside-2025s-4-biggest-trends/ ; https://www.techtarget.com/searchapparchitecture/tip/Treat-open-source-software-as-critical-infrastructure*

**Memory efficiency.** Token-efficient memory retrieval (~7k tokens/retrieval versus ~26k for full-context) justifies treating memory as a first-class, pluggable efficiency lever. *Source: https://mem0.ai/blog/state-of-ai-agent-memory-2026*

## Appendix G — Glossary

- **Core / kernel** — the minimal, non-replaceable heart of Wyrtloom: bootstrap mechanism plus stable interface contracts.
- **Contract** — a versioned interface promise. Stable across installations so plugins remain portable.
- **Plugin** — any swappable implementation behind a core contract. SAFE (sandboxed, no system access) or UNSAFE (declares capabilities, needs human approval).
- **Capability** — a declared system permission an UNSAFE plugin requires (file, network, shell, git…).
- **Task profile** — the environment shaping an agent's run: its tools, its context budget, and its escalation threshold.
- **Pre-digestion pipeline** — `parse → plan → execute → verify`; deterministic work first, LLM only at decision points.
- **Stamp** — a security assertion that a given *form* of a message passed the gate; voided on transformation.
- **Code crystallisation** — promoting a recurring expensive LLM pattern into cheap deterministic code.
- **The car park** — the phased roadmap of designed-but-not-yet-built requirements (Appendix E).
- **The two lenses** — the Bootstrap Lens and the Ecosystem Lens, the tests for whether something belongs in core.

